            <article data-uuid="110350579d594ea380244acb7d6b331b">
                <h3 class="eq" data-uuid="b86373c6ec424a21adfe295531cd7529">Essential Question</h3>
                <h3 class="eqt" data-uuid="5022a214486d48849402d84eae4d8c82">Did compromise make
                    the U.S. Constitution stronger or weaker?</h3>
                <p data-uuid="b2bd3cb7083940f4b3fa451d668e6435">When
                    the first U.S. government was created in 1777, the former colonies were in the
                    midst of a desperate fight to preserve their independence from Britain. After
                    achieving victory in the Revolutionary War, Americans found that the government
                    was too weak to handle problems that the nation faced. In 1787 delegates from
                    all thirteen states gathered in Philadelphia to create a new Constitution.
                    Because interests varied from state to state, the delegates negotiated several
                    important compromises over issues such as representation in Congress, slavery,
                    and taxation. Did these compromises weaken the Constitution, or did they lead
                    to a better government for the United States?&#160;</p>
                <p data-uuid="a84475bfc86543d2ad9f1dcb2b555bd8">As you read this module, look for
                    information about the ideas that inspired the Constitution, the issues that
                    divided Americans, and the effect each compromise had on our form of
                    government. When you are done, you will write a short essay answering the
                    Essential Question for this module.</p>
            </article>
            <section class="video-container " data-uuid="a984b948812848548cb6b02b01897287">
                <article data-uuid="46dfe2611cad44b59035720f162890f6">
                    <h3 class="vid" data-uuid="57c10080a8314d568bb3be749e2dc552">America
                        Gets a Constitution</h3>
                    <p class="vid" data-uuid="2a60f31cfbe2406db670a7f2669cf28a">Soon after the Revolutionary War ended, many Americans began to feel that the government they set up under the Articles of Confederation was not strong enough. In 1787 delegates from all 13 states drafted a new Constitution to “form a more perfect Union.”<br />
                    </p>
